##Karen Zhu Mingkang: I was locked up at home, playing a red cotton guitar with missing strings

Vicechina  

Function description, different color vision

At the beginning of the outbreak, we did not expect the situation to develop as it did later. At that time, we just paid our usual attention to our Hubei Friends? Everything okay at home? Be Safe out there. See you in a few years.

But it's getting harder every day. China's central provinces are locked down, families and friends are cut off, and friends in Hubei are separated from us by a river of uncertainty in just a few days.

Everyone was in the eye of the storm, but some were more in the turbulence at its center. As much as we fear for our own safety, we can not ignore their plight.

One of them was Huaren Guitarist Zhu Mingkang, an old colleague of ours. He left Beijing two years ago to work in Shenzhen, and has recorded for the band every time he returns to Beijing. The last time I saw him, he was recorded at the Jager Hunt last year.

After a farewell to contact, he has reported 711 confirmed cases in Yichang, Hubei (as of 11:00 on February 9) has been blocked for 15 days, since "time is plenty" , we asked him to say the things that have been on his mind for more than 10 days. Here's what he said.

Happy New Year, other friends. I am now in Yichang, Hubei Province, and have not been out of the city for ten days due to the closure of the city and the ban on travel. I wanted to bring my guitar on my return trip. I stayed home during the Spring Festival to play the piano, but I felt a little anxious before I went home during the Spring Festival. Plus, my mother had just had a major operation in the second half of last year. I wanted to go home early to spend time with my family. My plane ticket left in the middle of the night, i didn't even make it to the company convention, and when I got home, I forgot my guitar.

A Fender Nissan Jazzmaster used by Zhu Mingkang

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The day after I returned to Yichang, Wuhan was declared a closed city. My first reaction was that it turned out to be more serious than anything we had seen on television or on the Internet. After paying attention to a few of my old friends who still work in Wuhan, some of whom work in the executive branch, some of whom are in the pharmaceutical business, their replies were grim, angry, and worried.

Within a day or two of the city's closure, counties and cities on the Yichang side were also on alert, with local governments posting news of outbreaks and prevention messages on Wechat. I also went out as usual in those days to prepare New Year goods for my family. I went to the drugstore twice and finally got a mask. I told my family not to go out. I told my relatives not to go out. But it was not until the second day of the Lunar New Year that the elderly people on the street began to wear masks. On the third day of the third lunar month, traffic on our side of the road was closed, traffic was banned, the Three Gorges Airport also issued a notice to close the airport, and then the street was completely deserted.

I went back to Yichang to live with my parents. My mom is recovering from surgery and needs a year's rest, so for the better part of last year, my mom and dad rarely go out, and they are relatively comfortable staying at home. Even if they don't know what "nerd" means. This TV is a bit more bitter, home TV has been seen bad, years later have to change.

Photo courtesy of interviewees

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
You asked me how I was the other day, and I said, "stuck at home sulking, " and I wondered where that Sulk came from. If is a understanding person's words, will have one kind of mood, this Spring Festival's mood is really very complex. The bombardment of information on social networks is an explosion of social sentiment and a reflection of the group's mental state. Leaving aside the base and superstructure at the national level, it forced me to reflect on my industry and my daily life. On the one hand, the epidemic in my hometown is severe, people are in a state of panic, powerlessness and despair, while some colleagues from far and wide are still joking and telling jokes, the "friends" in the circle of friends who yearn for the exquisite life still send themselves far away from the overseas life of virus. Isn't it true that many of us have been talking about empathy in the workplace and in relationships for years, but does it make sense in the face of real life and disaster?

Of course, I have no right to blame anyone or interfere with anyone. After all, this is everyone's life, and I certainly hope that everyone can live in peace and comfort, free from disease and disaster. We can physically isolate the virus, but we can not isolate the mental pollution, which includes everything we've seen in the intervening years about the evils of consumption. I know not everyone cares about living sober, but I'm terrified that after this disaster, everyone will be smoking cigarettes under the office building, talking about their mortgage, their marriage, their happiness and unhappiness, and continue to treat yourself like a pig. "Buddhism" and "magic" are destroying the spirit of a generation, willing to think for themselves fewer and fewer people.

In addition, the most talked about topics in the last two years are about various Internet sinkholes, but when I saw the "hard-core slogans" on the Internet to prevent the epidemic in various places, i knew that it was the townsfolk, the villagers, and the stockade that were really heavy. Sitting in an office, plotting a descent, just building a car behind closed doors.

I spend most of my time with my parents, watching TV, and working from home. I am in the QQ music under the music playing platform Moo, mainly responsible for the content of the special topics inside, including playlists, interviews. The topics for the Spring Festival period were also prepared years ago, but seeing the reality of these days, we are adjusting every day, on the one hand, trying to make our topics as valuable as possible, avoiding those empty and inane contents, there will also be a selection of music that will encourage and ease people's emotional anxiety. Including blessing big Wuhan, the feeling of this Spring Festival, the homestead series and so on, "how to enhance the comfortable atmosphere of working from home" , "the small town life I yearn for" , "how does the music of the boy and girl with dreadlocks sound" and so on, my favorite was the "back to a minimalist" playlist, and a-year-old compilation of delicious and big hot dogs, "let's cut the party to the RAFFLE. ".

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
"I was on Facebook, checking the news, " and I saw a Massive Attack post about Andy Gill's death.

Moo also put out a playlist about Gang of Four's Andy Gill the day he died. I had just finished watching the Irishman the other night, and I was sad to hear that Andy had died. I remember the last time I shared his song, I was listening to Damaged Goods after working on the Vice China APP. But it turns out that no one really cared about Andy's death at this point, not to mention the fact that everyone had to accept Kobe's death. It depresses me to think that the next few years will probably see the departure of many more people we have followed and believed in for years to come. And look at our side of the country, Beat Generation.

Band life is kind of backwards at this point. My grandmother afraid I am bored, give me from the cabinet out of a red cotton card wooden guitar, is before an elder played, and burning stick similar, can not play a string. I spent the afternoon reworking it, and recently I've been playing it at home occasionally.

The time-traveling cotton-wool Guitar came in Handy

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Among Hualun's members, I returned to Yichang with Ding Mao, who had just returned to Beijing from his native Xi'an because he had to prepare ahead of time for his own operation, the Izakaya, which could be a difficult few months for the Izakaya owner. Bass player Wang Wei and drummer Wang Xu are still in town, and I'm guessing Wang Wei is staying home with the kids, and Wang Xu is updating his wild spot radio station. Years ago we had planned, if nothing else, to have a very different album this year.

In Times of crisis, if we stay at home and are comfortable, we can enjoy the music we like, but it doesn't mean anything to the patients and their families who are fighting on the front lines and living in fear. For onlookers on the periphery, it has become a show-off tool. Take a look at the latest new songs released on the mainland. Apart from the artistic sense, will those who really need cheering and encouragement listen to these things? Do people who want strength and courage in their hearts need them?

An interview with Ryuichi Sakamoto on Weibo happened to mention that he knew the true power of music, so he never abused it. I also don't want professors to be interpreted as particularly young and idolized in China.

To be honest, I don't know what I can do for the people on the front lines, the broken families and the cities, but I do know what not to do at this moment.

We were young at the time of the Wenchuan County earthquake, and soon began a small contribution at VOX in Wuhan. But now, I think we'll do something else for the city.

I hope that people like me, who are in isolation and under lock and key, don't run around, take good care of themselves at home, and use this time to reacquaint themselves with themselves, their environment, and plan whether what they are going to do next makes sense. When I get back to Yichang, I always go to the riverbank for a lap. After the closure, I want to go for a spring outing on my bicycle and have a good experience of what a healthy world looks like. And clean up your circle of friends, because some people are just stupid.

But that doesn't matter. It's good to know there's no bad news about the outbreak getting out of hand, right?
